04149nam a22005055i 9780773561632DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19881988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735616327 a10.1515/97807735616322doi  a(DE-B1597)657959  a(OCoLC)1394872435  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD2429.C2bC65 1988eb 7aBUS0510002bisacsh04a322/.3/09711 aColeman, William D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBusiness and Politics :bA Study of Collective Action /cWilliam D. Coleman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1988] 4cÂ©1988  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tCollective Action by Business -- tThe Political Responsibility of Business -- tAn Overview of Business Associations -- tFramework for Analysis -- tPolicy Networks and Associative Action -- tBusiness Associations -- tGeneral Business Associations -- tAgriculture and Corporatism -- tConstruction -- tResources: Forestr and Mining -- tFinance: Clientelism and Self-Regulation -- tManufacturing: A Divided Community -- tBusiness and Society -- tFragmentation: Two Foreign Comparisons -- tState Institutions and Business Association -- tBusiness and Democracy -- tAssociation Domain 1867-1980 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on a survey of all national business associations, and interviews with many interest-group executives, Business and Politics outlines the wide variety of roles assumed by interest groups in the Canadian policy process. Coleman argues that the present fragmention of business interests makes consultation with major socio-economic producer groups highly unlikely. Instead, adjustment takes place as a series of ad hoc bailouts related to an electoral calculus rather than to a more reflective consideration of the longer-term evolution of the Canadian economy and the relative economic position of Canadians. As there are no organizations that prompt business to take a broad look at its responsibilities to society at large, some economic policy options that political leaders might want to consider are ruled out. Attempts to redress difficulties in the Canadian economy and social welfare system consequently suffer. Coleman concludes that the business community is not appropriately accountable to Canadians for its actions, nor is it sufficiently organized to assume the political responsibilities that come with the private economic power it possesses. He argues that Canada could benefit from examining models of the political institutions in smaller European states and adopting some of their solutions for reform in this country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Public Finance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356163240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561632/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles